description: From Latin penētrātus, past participle of penētrō (“to put, set, or place within, enter, pierce, penetrate”), from penes (“within, with”) by analogy to intrō (“to go in, enter”).

verbs.description: penetrate (third-person singular simple present penetrates, present participle penetrating, simple past and past participle penetrated)

entries.meaning: To enter into; to make way into the interior of; to pierce.
(figuratively) To achieve understanding of, despite some obstacle; to comprehend; to understand.
examples: I could not penetrate Burke's opaque rhetoric.

entries.meaning: To affect profoundly through the senses or feelings; to move deeply.
examples: to penetrate one's heart with pity

entries.meaning: To infiltrate an enemy to gather intelligence.
To insert the penis into an opening, such as a vagina, mouth or anus.
examples: a male elephant comes up and penetrates the female

entries.meaning: (chess) To move a piece past the defending pieces of one's opponent.
